Introduction¶

Dataset

This project analyzes the TMDB MOVIES dataset. The dataset contains information about 10,866 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user average ratings, bugdet and revenue. This analysis intends to find interesting trends in the dataset.

The tmdb dataset contains 21 attributes of 10,866 movies released from the year 1960 to 2015. These attributes include the

  1. id
  2. imdb_id
  3. popularity
  4. budget
  5. revenue
  6. original_title
  7. cast
  8. homepage
  9. director
  10. tagline
  11. keywords
  12. overview
  13. runtime
  14. genres
  15. production_companies
  16. release_date
  17. vote_count
  18. vote_average
  19. release_year
  20. budget_adj
  21. revenue_adj

Questions which this analysis will cover are

  1. What kind of properties are associated with movies that have high revenue?
  2. How does the average runtime of movies vary over the years?
  3. Who directed the most movies?
  4. Which genres appears mostly?
  5. What are the top 20 production companies with the highest number of releases?
  6. What is the relationship between popularity and the profit?
  7. What is the relationship between the budget and the profit?
  8. What is the relationship between average vote and the profit?
  9. Who was the most frequent actor?

Data Cleaning¶

Under data cleaning, the following things are done.

  1. I dropped the duplicate row
  2. I changed the format of the release_date column into the datetime format
  3. I removed all the unneeded columns that are not needed in the analysis
  4. I removed the movies which are having zero value of budget or revenue
  5. I replaced all the null values with "Unknown"

First of all I drop the duplicate rows with the line of code below

In [14]:
# dropping the duplicate values in the dataset

tmdb_data.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

Then I convert the release_date column into the datetime format

In [15]:
# converting the release_date column to datetime format

tmdb_data['release_date'] = pd.to_datetime(tmdb_data['release_date'])

I remove the unneeded columns in the line of code below

In [16]:
# dropping all the unneeded columns for the analysis

tmdb_data.drop(['homepage', 'tagline', 'overview', 'budget_adj', 'revenue_adj', 'imdb_id', 'vote_count'], axis=1, inplace=True)

As we have seen earlier, the dataset contains rows which have either the budget or the revenue equal to zero. I will assume that those movies were not released and hence remove them from the dataset in order to obtain correct and accurate analysis.

In [17]:
# first if all getting the indexes of those rows

ind_drop = tmdb_data.query("budget == 0 | revenue == 0").index
In [18]:
# dropping all the rows 

tmdb_data.drop(ind_drop, inplace=True)

Lastly I fill all null values with the value "Unknown"

In [19]:
# replacing null values with "Unknown"

tmdb_data.fillna('Unknown', inplace=True)

How does the average runtime of movies vary over the years?¶

In [42]:
# defining a function which will plot the trend of data feature over the years

def plot_trend_over_years(data, color, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    plot_ = data.plot(kind='line', color=color, marker='o', lw=3, xticks=data.index, figsize=(30,10), fontsize=18)
    plt.xticks(rotation=60)
    plot_.set_title(label=title, fontdict={'fontsize': 24}, loc='center')
    plot_.set_xlabel(xlabel, fontdict={'fontsize':24})
    plot_.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontdict={'fontsize':24})
    plt.show()
In [43]:
av_runtime_by_yr = tmdb_data.groupby('release_year')['runtime'].mean()

from collections import defaultdict

genre_appearances = defaultdict(int)

        genre_appearances[genre]+=1

# defining a function to create a bar plot from a dictionary

def plot_bar_from_dict(data, xlabel, ylabel, title, data_type='dict'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(25,10))
    if data_type == 'dict':
        plt.bar(x=data.keys(), height=data.values())
    elif data_type == 'list':
        plt.bar(x=list(data.keys())[:10], height=list(data.values())[:10])
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontdict={'fontsize': 20})
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontdict={'fontsize': 20})
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xticks(rotation=50, fontsize=20)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=18)
    plt.show()

In [68]:
def plot_reg(x, y, data, xlabel, ylabel, title, color=None):
    _, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20,8))
    sns.regplot(x=x, y=y, data=data, ax=ax, color=color)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

actor_appearances = defaultdict(int)

    for actor in actor_list:
        actor_appearances[actor]+=1

sorted_actor_appearances = dict(sorted(actor_appearances.items(), key = lambda x: x[1], reverse=True))

Conclusions¶

After cleaning the dataset, the following results were made from the analysis¶

  • Most companies generate a lesser revenue.
  • Movies produced by Walt Disney Pictures, Pixar Animation Studios,DreamWorks Animation, Marvel Studios, Walt Disney Feature Animation, Eon Productions, Blue Sky Studios, Twentieth Century Fox Animation, Universal Pictures, Illumination Entertainment, Walt Disney Animation Studios, Lucasfilm, Paramount Pictures tend to have high revenue
  • The average runtime of movies tend to decrease over the years
  • The year 1965 had the highest number of released movies
  • Steven Spielberg directed the most movies followed by Clint Eastwood and Ridley Scott
  • Throughout the years 1960 to 2015, the Drama genre appeared mostly followed by the Comdey genre and the Thriller genre
  • Universal Pictures had the most number of movie releases followed by Warner Bros and Paramount Pictures
  • High profit is associated with high popularity because of the moderately strong correlation that exists between them
  • High profit is associated with high budget becuase of the moderately strong correlation between the two features
  • A high average vote is weakly associated with a high profit because of the weak correlation between the variables
  • Robert De Niro acted in most movies followed by Bruce Wills and Samuel L. Jackson

Limitations¶

Some assumptions were made during the analysis which may not make the results of the analysis 100 percent accurate. For instance, it was assumed that movies with 0 value of budget or revenue were not released and so they not included in our analysis, also null values were replaced with "Unknown". Nonetheless, the overall results of the analysis shows the general trend of released movies
